title: For Sale:  Citadel 1911 - $475
postcontent: Up for sale is a Citadel 1911 Officer Sized Anyone familiar with "budget" 1911s will know of Rock Island Armory and how they're great reliable guns for an affordable cost. This is their sister company, and yes they're both produced in the phillipines. However, the Citadel is considered the slightly nicer version of the RIA models, with their sights cut out for NOVAK and Dovetailed so that they fit regular stock 1911 sights. This gun was my EDC, so it comes with a couple extra accessories that I'll be throwing in for no extra charge. The TFO night sights are still new (about a year old), so the tritium is still good at night, and the fiber optics pull light during the day and you really grab a fast sight picture because of it. title: For Sale:  Winchester M1917 U.S. Rifle
postcontent: Winchester M1917 U.S. Rifle, AKA the American Enfield. Originally produced by U.S. manufacturers as the Pattern 1914 Enfield rifle in .303 caliber for the British military, after the U.S. entered WWI many of these rifles were produced instead in the U.S. .30-06 caliber and used by the U.S. Army to speed arming the rapidly growing military. This is why the internal magazine holds an odd 6 rounds instead of the usual 5 (the British .303 round is rimmed, while the .30-06 round is not, taking up less space hence 1 more round). By the end of the war most of the American Expeditionary Force carried the M1917 rifle than the M1903 Springfield. As stated, this was made by Winchester making an even MORE desirable rifle. Great finish, beautiful wood, strong rifling, Winchester barrel dated 9-18. Remington bolt. Plenty of strong cartouches and proof marks.  I will also include a Remington made M1913 bayonet dated 4-17 with British proof marks.
